We’ll first read in the data. These data reflect an abbreviated version of the Lancaster Sensorimotor norms by Lynott et al 2019. The Lancaster norms reflect subjective crowdsourced ratings of the salience of many English words on vision, audition, olfaction, etc.

1 Assumptions

Parametric model assumptions (see Field et al, Chapter 5)
1) Normally distributed
2) Homogeneity of variance across groups
3) Interval or ratio scale
4) Independence

Let’s take these one at a time using the Lancaster norms as a test case

1.1 Normality

1.1.1 Histogram of visual salience across English words

Let’s first visualize the distribution using a histogram and overlay a normal curve over the distribution. To do this, we need to plot density and not frequency. Let’s overlay a normal curve and take a guess. That looks pretty darn normal to me.

ggplot(Lancaster, aes(x = Visual)) + geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), colour = "black", 
    fill = "goldenrod2", binwidth = 0.1) + xlab("Likert Rating") + ylab("Density") + 
    jamie.theme + ggtitle("Visual Salience across English Words") + stat_function(fun = dnorm, 
    args = list(mean = mean(Lancaster$Visual), sd = sd(Lancaster$Visual)), color = "red", 
    size = 1)

1.1.2 QQplot

Let’s run a qqplot on all that visual data

qplot(sample = Lancaster$Visual, stat = "qq")

1.1.3 Normality statistics (Shapiro Wilk)

Shapiro Wilk Test – null hypothesis is no difference (i.e., normal). It won’t work on large samples (>5k) but let’s try it out on a smaller distribution we know to be normal

bell <- rnorm(5000, 5, 1)  #here's a fake dataset, sampling 5000 random normally distributed numbers with a mean of 5 and an sd=1
shapiro.test(bell)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  bell
## W = 0.99966, p-value = 0.5934

1.1.4 Histograms of multiple variables at once

We will use the facet wrap function to do this. Use the long form dataframe

all <- ggplot(long, aes(x = rating), fill = modality) + geom_histogram(aes(y = ..count..), 
    binwidth = 0.1, color = "black", fill = "goldenrod2") + xlab("Likert Rating") + 
    ylab("Count") + jamie.theme + ggtitle("Histograms of Modalities across English Words") + 
    facet_wrap(~modality, nrow = 2)
all

1.2 Equal Variance

1.2.1 Boxplot for coarse inspection

All levels of the factor variables should have equal variance
First let’s coarsely eyeball the variance of the groups by each sensory modality

boxplot(long$rating ~ long$modality, col = "red")

1.2.2 Levene Test

Null hypothesis is the no difference hypothesis

leveneTest(long$rating, long$modality, center = mean)
## Levene's Test for Homogeneity of Variance (center = mean)
##           Df F value    Pr(>F)    
## group      5  4958.3 < 2.2e-16 ***
##       238224                      
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

1.3 Interval or ratio scale

Self explanatory

1.4 Independence

Self-explanatory. Each word is its own independent observation in the Lancaster normns. There is no temporal autocorrelation.

2 Outliers & Outlier detection

Let’s create a univariate distribution – shoe sizes. 1.5*IQR is a univariate outlier using the boxplot method. the mean method is >2sds

set.seed(129)
shoes <- data.frame(sizes = c(sample(12, 20, replace = T), 30), type = rep("nike", 
    21))
head(shoes)
##   sizes type
## 1     2 nike
## 2     4 nike
## 3     2 nike
## 4     4 nike
## 5     2 nike
## 6     7 nike
ggplot(shoes, aes(x = type, y = sizes), fill = sizes) + geom_point(shape = 21, 
    color = "black", size = 2.3, alpha = 0.6, position = position_jitter(w = 0.03, 
        h = 0)) + ylab("shoe sizes") + jamie.theme

summary(shoes)
##      sizes          type   
##  Min.   : 1.000   nike:21  
##  1st Qu.: 2.000            
##  Median : 5.000            
##  Mean   : 6.429            
##  3rd Qu.: 9.000            
##  Max.   :30.000
shoes.z <- shoes %>% mutate(zsize = scale(shoes$sizes))  #generates a new dataframe with the z-scores for shoe sizes as a new variable you can sort on or filter on

2.1 Eliminating outliers z>2

We can just throw them out by filtering or applying a simple if then statement

shoes.small <- shoes.z %>% filter(zsize <= 2)  #creates a new dataframe returning only shoe sizes z<2 in the original distribution
summary(shoes.small)
##      sizes         type          zsize.V1      
##  Min.   : 1.00   nike:20   Min.   :-0.8524166  
##  1st Qu.: 2.00             1st Qu.:-0.6953925  
##  Median : 4.50             Median :-0.3028322  
##  Mean   : 5.25             Mean   :-0.1850641  
##  3rd Qu.: 7.50             3rd Qu.: 0.1682401  
##  Max.   :12.00             Max.   : 0.8748486

3 Transformations

Need to be done on all the variables not just one. Let’s look at the olfactory ratings.

ggplot(Lancaster, aes(x = Olfactory)) + geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), 
    colour = "black", fill = "green", binwidth = 0.1) + xlab("Likert Rating") + 
    ylab("Density") + jamie.theme + ggtitle("Olfactory Salience across English Words") + 
    stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = mean(Lancaster$Olfactory), 
        sd = sd(Lancaster$Olfactory)), color = "black", size = 1)

3.1 Natural log transform

For illustrative purposes I have created a new dataframe with just smell and visual ratings on English words. This transform is good for positively skewed data – long tail to right. There’s a problem here in that we have some zero observations

brief <- Lancaster %>% select(1, 6, 7)
length(which(brief$Olfactory == 0))  #counts the number of rows with a 0 observation
## [1] 8993
brief$log <- log(brief$Olfactory + 1)  #log is natural log, log10 is log base 10, this adds 1 so that there is never a 0 observation
ggplot(brief, aes(x = log)) + geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), colour = "black", 
    fill = "green", binwidth = 0.1) + ylab("Density") + jamie.theme + ggtitle("Log olfactory Salience") + 
    stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = mean(brief$log), sd = sd(brief$log)), 
        color = "black", size = 1)

3.2 Square root transformation

You don’t have to worry about zeros

brief$sqrt <- sqrt(brief$Olfactory)
head(brief)
##        Word  Olfactory   Visual        log      sqrt
## 1  AARDVARK 1.25000000 4.125000 0.81093022 1.1180340
## 2     ABACK 0.00000000 2.823529 0.00000000 0.0000000
## 3    ABACUS 0.11111111 3.944444 0.10536052 0.3333333
## 4   ABANDON 0.05882353 2.176471 0.05715841 0.2425356
## 5 ABANDONED 0.00000000 2.777778 0.00000000 0.0000000
## 6 ABANDONEE 0.25000000 3.937500 0.22314355 0.5000000
ggplot(brief, aes(x = sqrt)) + geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), colour = "black", 
    fill = "green", binwidth = 0.1) + ylab("Density") + jamie.theme + ggtitle("Sqrt olfactory Salience") + 
    stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = mean(brief$sqrt), sd = sd(brief$sqrt)), 
        color = "black", size = 1)

3.3 Reciprocal transformation

Doesn’t work when there are zeros in the denominator

brief$recip <- 1/(brief$Olfactory + 1)
head(brief)
##        Word  Olfactory   Visual        log      sqrt     recip
## 1  AARDVARK 1.25000000 4.125000 0.81093022 1.1180340 0.4444444

## 3    ABACUS 0.11111111 3.944444 0.10536052 0.3333333 0.9000000

## 5 ABANDONED 0.00000000 2.777778 0.00000000 0.0000000 1.0000000
## 6 ABANDONEE 0.25000000 3.937500 0.22314355 0.5000000 0.8000000
ggplot(brief, aes(x = recip)) + geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), colour = "black", 
    fill = "green", binwidth = 0.1) + ylab("Density") + jamie.theme + ggtitle("Reciprocal olfactory Salience") + 
    stat_function(fun = dnorm, args = list(mean = mean(brief$recip), sd = sd(brief$recip)), 
        color = "black", size = 1)
